				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="769063"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1502674004 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">14 Aug 2017 01:26</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3570166">
									

<p>To use a GOC lens here,</p>
<p>At the time that these bioprinters were recovered, shortly following the effective destruction of Prometheus Labs (in the 90s or early turn of the millennium), such advances, particularly within the field of stem cell manipulation and artificial cellular superstructure construction, would be seen as too advanced for the rest of the world to know, and would have been classified as +2Gen: too advanced for the rest of the world to know and utilize at this time. This would've held until recently (within the last 5-10 years), particularly with the expiration of the FDM patent.</p>
<p>In 1989, S. Scott Crump patented the (then-unnamed) Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) process that is common to most 3D printers today<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-148051-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-148051-1')">1</a></sup>. This provided the Foundation with an effective buffer - with a monopoly on one of the key components critical to the bioprinter concept, any attempt at uncontained replication of the technology was effectively shut down. This gave the Foundation years to test what they possessed, which also matched development of mechatronics and cellular biology/biomedical engineering.</p>
<p>In 2007, Organovo was created<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-148051-2" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-148051-2')">2</a></sup>, which specialized in a method of creating 3D biological prints for experimentation, which effectively downgraded the +2Gen rating to +1Gen - advanced, but not so farfetched to seem anomalous anymore. It took years for conventional human understanding to catch up, but in 2007, the knowledge base finally caught up with what the Prometheus Labs researchers were conceiving decades before.</p>
<p>With the expiration of the FDM patent in 2009<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-148051-3" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-148051-3')">3</a></sup>, other companies began to get involved, effectively turning additive manufacturing as a whole to current generation status (Gen0) and progressing 3D bioprinting itself from cutting edge to more conventional status - still at +1Gen, but becoming more understandable and progressing to Gen0 status. The research put into stem cells and cellular manipulation would also serve to make such devices conventional now.</p>
