<blockquote>
<p>Keep in mind that the Foundation's explicit goal is to preserve normalcy. That means keeping super-advanced tech secret even if it's not necessarily anomalous because it would be extremely disruptive to the status quo.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>If the Foundation was in the habit of doing these sorts of things, they'd be regularly intervening in non-anomalous affairs in order to keep things &quot;normal.&quot; You'd have them working to prevent cultures from changing because they saw the new state as abnormal; they'd regularly intervene in governments to try and keep &quot;abnormal&quot; politicians from gaining power. Should the Foundation have prevented both World Wars because of the political and economic disruption they caused? What about the decline of colonialism, or the Russian Revolution, or the fall of the Soviet Union? Did the Foundation try and fail to contain the knowledge of nuclear weaponry?</p>
<p>They'd also have to define when society was &quot;ready&quot; for this new technology, and we're given absolutely no insights into why the Foundation considers it acceptable to allow the tech to exist in 2007 after classifying it as an SCP object in&#8230; well, we don't actually know when the device was found.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If someone invented a Star Trek-like nanofactory tomorrow, even if they could explain how it worked perfectly and the Foundation confirmed it all via their own research, they would still lock it and its inventor up because of the insane political and economic disruption suddenly introducing that level of tech would cause.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The article also states that the technology was considered anomalous, though. We're given no indication of why that is, and &quot;It would be bonkers&quot; doesn't cut it.</p>

