<blockquote>
<p>The article also states that the technology was considered anomalous, though. We're given no indication of why that is, and &quot;It would be bonkers&quot; doesn't cut it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The thing is, 20 years ago this was at best vaguely plausible comic-book science: tech you'd see alongside fusion reactors and sapient AI. I could give you a dozen reasons why this technology shouldn't work&#8230; most of which have been addressed in the past couple years by breakthroughs that sound like stuff straight out of Prometheus Labs. For instance, a proprietary <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrigel">protein slurry harvested from a line of mouse cancer cells</a> that just happens to be an ideal media for tissue culturing.</p>

