														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3570749">
									

<p>I have to agree with Roget and Scorpion.</p>
<p>The Foundation is, for all intents and purposes, the Illuminati. They're not against progress, because progress is considered normal, but a catastrophically disruptive tech boom is something to be actively avoided.</p>
<p>Yes, there is a degree of capriciousness to these judgements, and ultimately it's a bald guy at a desk deciding what's okay and what's not, but that's how they roll.</p>
<p>Should they have prevented the development of nuclear weapons? How do you know they didn't contribute to their development to ensure an Allied victory? Sounds like the kind of thing they would do. Preserving Colonialism may have been seen as not worth the effort. Remember, the Foundation is coldly practical. If preserving something will cost them more than it's worth, they're not going to do it. As for Russia/Soviet Union, they likely wouldn't have cared about a peasant uprising in a then backwater country, and the end of the Cold War would have been viewed as a good thing. Again, these are judgement calls being made by a bald guy at a desk, and you may not agree with him, but he's still going to do it.</p>
<p>As for your second point, the Foundation does contain People of Interest, not all of whom are anomalous (Dick C Normus, for instance) and no small number of whom are out for power, political or otherwise. Some anomalies are entire villages or tribes or even societies. Take <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-752">SCP-752</a> for instance. They themselves are not anomalous. Deviant from the norm, but not anomalous. Neither they nor their tech are supernatural, but the Foundation keeps their city under lock and key because of how disruptive their existence would be.</p>
<p>Finally, 'Bonkers' may be vague, but in this sense super advanced tech is like porn: hard to define, but you know it when you see it. I stand by my previously made points.</p>

							</div>

								
					
